      "topic": "stability-of-intermediate",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>Carbanion means a carbon atom carrying a negative charge. Such a species is stable when this negative charge is reduced (spread out) or pulled away.</p>\n<p>If a group attached to the carbanion is <b>electron withdrawing</b> (shows $-I$ effect), it pulls electron density towards itself. This reduces the negative charge on carbon, so the <b>carbanion becomes more stable</b>.</p>\n<p>If a group attached to the carbanion is <b>electron donating</b> (shows $+I$ effect), it pushes electron density towards the carbon. This increases the negative charge on carbon, so the <b>carbanion becomes less stable</b>.</p>\n<p>So, while arranging in decreasing order of stability: carbanions with stronger electron withdrawing groups will be more stable, and those with electron donating groups will be less stable.</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
